SIMPLE: clearing
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Clearing
<hw>Clear"ing</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act or process of
making clear.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The better <qex>clearing</qex> of this point.</q>
<rj><qau>South.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A tract of land cleared of wood for
cultivation.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A lonely <qex>clearing</qex> on the shores of Moxie Lake.</q>
<rj><qau>J. Burroughs.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A method adopted by banks and bankers for making an
exchange of checks held by each against the others, and settling
differences of accounts.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ In England, a similar method has been adopted by
railroads for adjusting their accounts with each other.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>The gross amount of the balances adjusted in the
clearing house.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Clearing house</b></col>, <cd>the establishment where the
business of clearing is carried on. See <er>above</er>,
<er>3</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Clearly</ent>⟦br⟧
